<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-122-127 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 361 865</DOCID><JOURNAL>Windows Watcher  July 1991 v1 n9 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT CompuTh!nk Incorporated 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Coalitions vie for object standards. (Tools Watch)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Object Design Inc. (Management)NCR Corp. (Management)Hewlett-Packard Co. (Management)Sun Microsystems Inc. (Management)Borland International Inc. (Standards).andO;Ticker:    IBM; SUNW; HWP; NCR; BORL.andO;Topic:     Object-Oriented ProgrammingStandardizationConsortiaObject Management GroupMembership ListTrade and Professional Associations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Industry alliances continue to shift as major companies grapple overstandards for object-oriented programming.andP;  Nearly everyone agrees that weneed standards.andP;  At issue is whose standards to use.andM;Object-oriented programming is more efficient because it allows the creationof reuseable chunks of code.andP;  With standards, objects created with oneprogramming language could be used with another, vastly improvingproductivity.andM;In one recent development, four companies joined forces to proposespecifications to the Object Management Group (OMG), an internationalorganization set up to establish and publish specifications.andP;  NCR, ObjectDesign, Hewlett-Packard, and Sun Microsystems will cooperate to proposestandards to allow objects to work on networks made up of different hardwareplatforms and operating systems.andM;IBM joined OMG on June 5th.andP;  Some observers say the move is part of IBM'sattempts to get more development tools for its Presentation Managerinterface.andP;  Supporting open standards might make Presentation Manager morepalatable to users, and to the companies that create and sell programmingtools.andM;Borland, a member since 1989, has submitted its ObjectWindows softwareinterface to OMG as an open standard.andP;  But Microsoft, who joined onlyrecently, has proposed different standards.andP;  Borland has publicly takenexception to Microsoft's suggestions, claiming they are technicallydeficient.andP;  Borland also contends that Microsoft's proposals are a stallingtactic.andP;  While other companies are scrambling to retrofit Microsoft's newstandards, Microsoft will have time to get its own object-oriented languagesto market, Borland says.andM;Borland believes its own standards should form the standard because italready sells object-oriented programming products.andP;  andless;D%-2andgt;andM;But Microsoft's proposals recently got a boost when Digital Equipment Corp.andO;announced that it will support Microsoft's Object Linking and Embeddingspecifications.andP;  In its own defense, Microsoft denies Borland's claims thatits proposed standards are part of a Machiavellian scheme.andP;  They say it tiesin with their previously announced Open Tools strategy, which encourages andassists other companies to build development tools for -Windows.andM;Although the work on standardization is a positive step, it will not becompletely successful if some of the major players refuse to endorse it.andP;  Itis unknown at this time whether companies such as IBM, Borland, Microsoft,and NCR will abide by the standards if their own proposals are rejected bythe committee.andO;</TEXT></DOC>